Q: Getting Deprecation Warning with Electron Builder A: <p>You got clear recommendation on how to show where the warning was created:</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>node --trace-deprecation your-build-script.js
</code></pre>
<p>Typically, your execute such a node application in the console and look at the output. Everything you can trace using this or other trace options will be shown in the console.</p>
<p>I don't know where the warning is created, but it is pretty much clear how to use the recommended option. To understand it, please see the <a href="https://www.electron.build/index.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Electron builder documentation</a>. Pay attention that you can use two very similar APIs. The documentation names them <em>Command Line Interface (CLI)</em> and <em>Programmatic API</em>.</p>
<p>You can package your Electron application using CLI if you pre-install the builder, using the CLI command <code>electron-builder build</code>, but you are using <code>npx</code>, which is the most basic way of performing the build.</p>
<h2>Using Programmatic API</h2>
<p>To use the node flag <code>--trace-deprecation</code> and other flags, you can use the <em>Programmatic API</em>. Basically, you have to pre-install the builder and use in in your node application, for example, <code>your-build-script.js</code>. It can look like</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>&quot;use strict&quot;;

const builder = require(&quot;electron-builder&quot;);
const Platform = builder.Platform;

// define all the options

builder.build({
  targets: Platform.MAC.createTarget(),
  config: options
})
.then((result) =&gt; {
  console.log(JSON.stringify(result))
})
.catch((error) =&gt; {
  console.error(error)
})
</code></pre>
<p>This is a slightly modified example from <a href="https://www.electron.build/programmatic-usage" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://www.electron.build/programmatic-usage</a>. Please see this page, as well as the detailed API description.</p>
<h2>Using NODE_OPTIONS and npx</h2>
<p>Alternatively, you can use npx and <code>NODE_OPTIONS</code> argument.</p>
<p>For example (Bash):</p>
<pre class="lang-bash prettyprint-override"><code>NODE_OPTIONS=&quot;--trace-deprecation&quot; npx electron-builder build ...
</code></pre>
<h2>Other tools</h2>
<p>Other options include using tools like <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/cross-env" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>cross-env</code></a>. I never tried it, but this tool offers the way to define node options in the file <code>package.json</code>. Please see the <code>cross-env</code> documentation for the details.</p>

Q: TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading &#39;data&#39;) console.log(data) isnt returning user information A: <p>I had the same error,
in my project I was using axios in an async function with await command as below
(bmUserApi is an api library which I coded myself over axios )</p>
<pre><code>onLogin = async(formValues) =&gt; {

    this.setState({loading:true, error: &quot;&quot;});    

    try {

        var ls_response = await bmUserApi.login(formValues);

        this.setState({loading: false});

        const lv_token = ls_response.headers['x-auth-token'];
        Redux_Set_User(lv_token, this.props.redux_dispatch, this.props.history);   
</code></pre>
<p>when I was checking the error position on Google Chrome in &quot;Call Stack&quot; part, I've seen that my api library was trying add to authentication token to the api call header, by reading from localStorage of the browser.</p>
<p>I was doing it by using axios interceptors as below :</p>
<pre><code>axiosClient.interceptors.request.use( 
    async function(config) {

        config.headers = {
            'Content-Type': 'application/json'
        }

        // token :

        var ls_user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('user'));        

        const authToken = ls_user.token;

        if (authToken) 
            config.headers['x-auth-token'] = authToken;

        return config;
    },

    error =&gt; { Promise.reject(error) }
)
</code></pre>
<p>But this is login call .. so off course there is no stored data and token on the browser yet.  So the &quot;ls_user&quot; variable in the above code was null .. this was causing the error.  I just added control before that.</p>
<p>I hope this can be useful to your case.</p>
